'''Stack Soap''' is a [[personal care product]] developed to solve the issue of soap waste when an old bar of soap wears thin and would otherwise be discarded.<ref name="Gizmodo 7-25">{{cite web|last=Liszewski|first=Andrew|title=One Groove Turns Soap Bar Slivers into Infinite Soap|url=https://gizmodo.com/5885337/one-groove-turns-soap-bar-slivers-into-infinite-soap|publisher=Gizmodo|accessdate=25 July 2012}}</ref>  Stack Soap implements a grooved stack design such as that used with [[Pringles#Development|Pringles chips]] to merge an old, thin bar of soap with a new one.<ref name="Atlantic 2-15">{{cite news|last=Garber|first=Megan|title=Meet the Pringles of Personal Hygiene|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2012/02/meet-the-pringles-of-personal-hygiene/253136/|accessdate=25 July 2012|newspaper=The Atlantic|date=February 15, 2012}}</ref>

The concept was successfully pitched on [[Kickstarter]] in 2012,<ref>{{cite web|last=Norine|first=Aric|title=Soap bars that join together - STACK|url=http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/1627046474/stack-soap-bars-that-combine-no-wasted-or-broken-p|publisher=Kickstarter|accessdate=30 July 2012|date=8 February 2012}}</ref> and the product was featured in various media outlets including ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' magazine, ''[[The Atlantic]]'', [[Gizmodo]], and market research firm [[Mintel]].<ref name="Wired July">{{cite news|last=Hitt|first=Jack|title=A nation of Tinkerers|newspaper=Wired Magazine|date=July 2012}}</ref><ref name="StackSoap Press">{{cite web|title=STACK Soap press|url=http://www.stacksoap.com/press.html|publisher=StackSoap|accessdate=25 July 2012}}</ref>

