'''The Pee Pocket''' is a single-use urinary device that allows a person to stand while urinating, in situations where they could not normally do so. It was developed by a team of doctors and it is marketed primarily to women, athletes, travelers, the elderly, disabled, pregnancy, parents of young girls, and post-surgery patients. It can also be used to prevent the exchange of bodily fluids between people through contact with unsanitary surfaces. In 2014, when media reported an increase of [[Ebola virus disease|Ebola]] cases around the world, the Pee Pocket was said to help prevent the disease{{Citation needed|date=February 2017}}.
'''The Pee Pocket''' has also become very popular in the LGBTQ community and is used in bathrooms world wide{{Citation needed|date=February 2017}}.

